sentences: William Randolph "Cozy" Cole (October 17, 1909 – January 9, 1981) was an American jazz drummer who worked with Cab Calloway and Louis Armstrong among others and led his own groups.
His first music job was with Wilbur Sweatman in 1928.
In 1930, he played for Jelly Roll Morton's Red Hot Peppers, recording an early drum solo on "Load of Cole".
He spent 1931–33 with Blanche Calloway, 1933–34 with Benny Carter, 1935–36 with Willie Bryant, 1936–38 with Stuff Smith's small combo, and 1938–42 with Cab Calloway.

In 1942, he was hired by CBS Radio music director Raymond Scott as part of network radio's first integrated orchestra.
The concert was produced by Leon Hefflin, Sr. on June 7, 1953.
Also featured that day were Roy Brown and his Orchestra, Don Tosti and His Mexican Jazzmen, Earl Bostic, Nat "King" Cole, and Shorty Rogers and his Orchestra.
The track peaked at No. 29 in the UK Singles Chart in 1958.
Cole's song "Turvy II" reached No. 36 in 1959.
Throughout the 1960s and 1970s he continued to perform in a variety of settings alongside names like Jonah Jones, Stuff Smith, and Cab Calloway.
Cole and Gene Krupa often played drum duets at the Metropole in New York City during the 1950s and 1960s.
In 1978, Capital University in Columbus, awarded Cole an honorary degree of Doctor of Musical Arts.
In 1981, he died of cancer in Columbus, Ohio.
